n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":10\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Political Animals''\n|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Mini-Series or a Movie\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":10\" />\n|-\n|[[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Movie/Miniseries Supporting Actress|Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Movie/Mini-Series Supporting Actress]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a487944/critics-choice-television-awards-2013-the-major-winners-and-nominees/|title=Critics' Choice TV Awards 2013: winners|last=Goodacre|first=Kate|date=2013-06-11|website=Digital Spy|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2015\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''Flowers in the Attic''\n|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress \u2013 Mini-Series or a Movie\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":10\" />\n|-\n|Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Movie/Mini-Series Supporting Actress\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/critics-choice-television-awards-2014-712986|title=Critics' Choice Television Awards 2014: Complete Winners List|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Mini-Series or Television Movie\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sag-award-winners-2015-screen-actors-guild-awards-winner-list-1201414657/|title=SAG Award Winners 2015: Full List|last=Staff|first=Variety|last2=Staff|first2=Variety|date=2015-01-26|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|''Mom''\n|[[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Guest Performer in a Comedy Series]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/critics-choice-awards-nominations-2016-full-list-1201666326/|title=Critics\u2019 Choice Awards Nominations: \u2018Mad Max\u2019 Leads Film; ABC, HBO, FX Networks & \u2018Fargo\u2019 Top TV|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|date=2015-12-14|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|''House of Cards''\n|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":10\" />\n|}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Burstyn, Ellen (2006). ''Lessons in Becoming Myself''. [[Riverhead Books]] (New York City, New York). {{ISBN|978-1-59448-929-7}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20110304105714/http://ellenburstyn.net/}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000995}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|36013}}\n* {{Allrovi person|9777}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = President of the [[Actors Studio]]\n | years  = 1994\u2013present\n | with   = [[Al Pacino]]<br />and [[Harvey Keitel]]\n | before = [[Paul Newman]]\n | after  = Incumbent\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = Artistic Director of the [[Actors Studio]]\n | years  = 1982\u20131988<br />2007\u2013present\n | with   = Al Pacino (1982)\n | before = [[Lee Strasberg]] (1982)<br />[[Carlin Glynn]] (2007)<br />[[Lee Grant]] (2007)\n | after  = [[Frank Corsaro]] (1988)<br />Incumbent\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Ellen Burstyn\n|list = \n{{AcademyAwardBestActress 1961-1980}}\n{{ACCT Best Actress}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Actress 1960-1979}}\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actress}}\n{{DramaDesk PlayOutstandingActress 1975-2000}}\n{{EmmyAward MiniseriesSupportingActress 2001\u20132025}}\n{{EmmyAward DramaGuestActress}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActressMotionPictureMusicalComedy 1961-1980}}\n{{IndependentSpiritBestFemaleLead 2000\u20132020}}\n{{Michigan Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Actress Motion Picture}}\n{{TonyAward PlayLeadActress 1947-1975}}\n}}\n{{Triple Crown of Acting winners}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burstyn, Ellen}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Detroit]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American people of Canadian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Pennsylvania Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American Universalists]]\n[[Category:American writers of Native American descent]]\n[[Category:Best Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Actress BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Actress Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Actress Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:Cass Technical High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Drama Desk Award winners]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead winners]]\n[[Category:Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or Movie Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American people of First Nations descent]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:In\u0101yati Sufis]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Method actors]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Ellen Burstyn\n| image                     = Ellen Burstyn at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival.jpg\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   = Burstyn at the May 1, 2009 [[Tribeca Film Festival]] premi\u00e8re of ''[[Poliwood (film)|Poliwood]]''\n| birth_name                = Edna Rae Gillooly\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|1932|12|7|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| nationality               = American\n| other_names               = Ellen McRae\n| education                 = [[Cass Technical High School]]\n| occupation                = Actress\n| years_active              = 1955\u2013present\n| spouse                    = {{marriage|William Alexander<br>|1950|1957|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Paul Roberts<br>|1958|1961|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Neil Nephew|Neil Burstyn]]<br>|1964|1972|reason=divorced}}\n| children                  = 1\n| module2      = {{infobox officeholder |embed=yes\n| office       = 10th [[President (corporate title)|President]] of the [[Actors' Equity Association]]\n| term_start   = 1982\n| term_end     = 1985\n| predecessor  = [[Theodore Bikel]]\n| successor    = [[Colleen Dewhurst]]\n| website                   =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ellen Burstyn''' (born '''Edna Rae Gillooly'''; December 7, 1932) is an American actress. She is known for her work in dramas, and portrayal of troubled women. Burstyn is the recipient of various accolades, and is among the few performers to have won [[Triple Crown of Acting|Academy, Emmy and Tony Awards]].\n\nBorn in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]], Burstyn left school and worked as a dancer and model. She made her stage debut on Broadway in 1957 and soon started to make appearances in television shows. Stardom followed soon after with her acclaimed role in ''[[The Last Picture Show]]'' (1971), which earned her an Academy Award nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]. Her next appearance in ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'' (1973)'','' earned her a second Best Actress nomination. The film has remained popular and several publications have regarded it as [[List of films considered the best|one of the greatest horror films of all time]]. She also starred in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]'' (1974), which won her the Academy Award for Best Actress.\n\nShe appeared in numerous television movies and gained further recognition from her performances in ''[[Same Time, Next Year (film)|Same Time, Next Year]]'' (1978), which won her a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award'','']] and ''[[Resurrection (1980 film)|Resurrection]]'' (1980)'', [[How to Make an American Quilt]]'' (1995)'','' and ''[[Requiem for a Dream|Requiem For a Dream]]'' (2000)''.'' For playing a lonely drug-addicted woman in the last one of these, she was again nominated for an Academy Award and a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]]. In the 2010s, she made appearances in television series including the political dramas, ''[[Political Animals (miniseries)|Political Animals]]'' and ''[[House of Cards (American TV series)|House of Cards]]'', which have earned her Emmy Award nominations. Since 2000, she has been co-president of the [[Actors Studio]], a drama school in [[New York City]]. In 2013, she was inducted into the [[American Theatre Hall of Fame]] for her work on stage. \n\n==Early life==\nBurstyn was born Edna Rae Gillooly in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], the daughter of Correine Marie ([[married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] Hamel) and John Austin Gillooly.<ref name=lessons>{{cite book| last=Burstyn| first=Ellen |title=Lessons in Becoming Myself| year=2007| publisher=Penguin| isbn=1-594-48268-3| page=4}}</ref> She has described her ancestry as \"Irish, French, [[Pennsylvania Dutch]], a little [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Canadian Indian]]\".<ref name=clark>Clark, John (October 19, 2009).[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/62762742.html?dids=62762742:62762742&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Oct+19%2C+2000&author=JOHN+CLARK&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Movies%3B+Independent+Minded%3B+Academy+Award+winner+Ellen+Burstyn%2C+a+'tough+cookie%2C'+is+back+with+two+gritty+films+and+a+TV+show.&pqatl=google Movies; Independent Minded; Academy Award Winner Ellen Burstyn, \"A 'Tough Cookie', Is Back with Two Gritty Films and a TV Show\"]([[Abstract (summary)|Abstract]]; {{subscription}} {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115195009/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/62762742.html?dids=62762742:62762742&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Oct+19%2C+2000&author=JOHN+CLARK&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Movies%3B+Independent+Minded%3B+Academy+Award+winner+Ellen+Burstyn%2C+a+'tough+cookie%2C'+is+back+with+two+gritty+films+and+a+TV+show.&pqatl=google |date=January 15, 2013 }} for full article). ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (''via'' ''[[ProQuest|ProQuest Archiver]]''). Retrieved December 20, 2009.</ref><ref name=time>[[Staff writer]] (February 17, 1975). [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,912880,00.html \"Show Business: Gillooly Doesn't Live Here Anymore\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205080527/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,912880,00.html |date=December 5, 2008 }}. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''. Retrieved December 20, 2009.</ref> Burstyn has an older brother, Jack, and a younger brother, Steve.<ref name=lessons /><ref>Burstyn 2007, p. 14</ref> Her parents divorced when she was young, and she and her brothers lived with their mother and stepfather.<ref name=lessons />\n\nBurstyn attended [[Cass Technical High School]], a [[university-preparatory school]] which allowed students to choose a specific field of study. Burstyn majored in fashion illustration.<ref>Burstyn 2007, p. 36</ref> In high school, she was a cheerleader, a member of the student council, and president of her drama club. She dropped out of high school during her senior year after failing her classes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Incorporated|first=|title=Britannica Book of the Year|year=1976|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|isbn=0-852-29311-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/britannicabookof1976ency/page/29 29]|url=https://archive.org/details/britannicabookof1976ency/page/29}}</ref><ref name=sweeney>{{cite news| title=Burstyn: Women must find own roles in movies| last=Sweeney| first=Louise| date=November 23, 1980| work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]| page=N2}}</ref> Soon afterwards, Burstyn worked as a dancer, and then a model until the age of 23.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Staff|first=Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/nov/05/guardianinterviewsatbfisouthbank|title=Ellen Burstyn|date=2000-11-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430200830/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/nov/05/guardianinterviewsatbfisouthbank|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She later relocated to [[Dallas]], where she continued modeling and worked in other fashion jobs before moving to New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/interview-ellen-burstyn-on-inside-the-actors-studio.html|title=Ellen Burstyn Talks Her Dogs, Cosmology, and Co-hosting Inside the Actors Studio|last=Seitz|first=Matt Zoller|date=2019-12-19|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302215605/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/interview-ellen-burstyn-on-inside-the-actors-studio.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1955 to 1956, Burstyn appeared as an \"away we go\" dancing girl on ''[[The Jackie Gleason Show]]'' under the name Erica Dean.<ref name=bio>[http://www.biography.com/people/ellen-burstyn-9542388 \"Ellen Burstyn Biography,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428010734/http://www.biography.com/people/ellen-burstyn-9542388 |date=April 28, 2015 }} Biography.com. Retrieved April 23, 2015.</ref> Burstyn then decided to become an actress and chose the name \"Ellen McRae\" as her professional name; she later changed her surname after her 1964 marriage to Neil Burstyn.<ref name=glover>{{cite news| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UTAqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w0YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6972,407534| title=Ellen Burstyn wants to be director| last=Glover| first=William| date=May 1, 1975| work=[[The Daily News (Kentucky)|Park City Daily News]]| page=28| accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1958\u20131970: Early work===\nBurstyn debuted on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 1957 and joined [[Lee Strasberg]]'s [[Actors Studio|The Actors Studio]]<!--n.b. there is no possessive in the studio's name--> in New York City in 1967. In 1975, she won a [[Tony Award]] for [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play]] for her performance in the comedy ''[[Same Time, Next Year (play)|Same Time, Next Year]],'' a role in which she would reprise in a [[Same Time, Next Year (film)|film adaptation in 1978]]. Starting in the late 1950s, and throughout the 1960s, Burstyn frequently played guest roles on a number of [[Prime time|primetime]] television shows, including ''[[Dr. Kildare (TV series)|Dr. Kildare]]'', ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'', ''[[Ben Casey]]'', ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', ''[[Wagon Train]]'', ''[[The Big Valley]]'', and ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]''. During 1964\u20131965, she had a recurring role as Dr. Kate Bartok on the [[National Broadcasting Company|NBC]] [[daytime television]] [[soap opera]] ''[[The Doctors (1963 TV series)|The Doctors]]''. In 1967\u20131968, she co-starred as Julie Parsons opposite [[Dale Robertson]] in the [[American Broadcasting Company (ABC)|ABC]] [[Westerns on television|Western]] ''[[The Iron Horse (TV series)|The Iron Horse]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=TrIspiOaqboC&pg=PA79#v=onepage Marill, Alvin H. ''Television Westerns: Six Decades of Sagebrush Sheriffs, Scalawags, and Sidewinders.''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125170936/https://books.google.com/books?id=TrIspiOaqboC&pg=PA79#v=onepage |date=November 25, 2015 }} Scarecrow Press, 2011, p. 79-80. {{ISBN|978-0-8108-8132-7}}.</ref> She was credited as Ellen McRae until 1967, when she and her then-husband Neil Nephew both changed their surname to Burstyn, and she began to be credited as Ellen Burstyn.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=SJKsBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA61#v=onepage Dern, Bruce, et al. ''Bruce Dern: A Memoir.''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125053443/https://books.google.com/books?id=SJKsBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA61#v=onepage |date=November 25, 2015 }} Univ. Press of Kentucky, 2014, p. 61. {{ISBN|978-0-470-10637-2}}.</ref>\n\n===1971\u20131981: Film breakthrough===\nAfter a number of small film roles, Burstyn gained recognition after starring in the 1971's ''[[The Last Picture Show]],'' a coming of age story, directed by [[Peter Bogdanovich]] and adapted from a semi-autobiographical 1966 novel by [[Larry McMurtry]]. The film earned critical acclaim for its nostalgia and visual style that is reminiscent of 1951, the year in which the plot takes place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-last-picture-show-1971|title=The Last Picture Show movie review (1971) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212015438/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-last-picture-show-1971|archive-date=December 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was nominated for eight [[Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]] for Burstyn and for co-star [[Cloris Leachman]]. Leachman won the award.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1998, the film was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]], being deemed \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/loc/lcib/9812/film.html|title=Hooray for Hollywood (December 1998) - Library of Congress Information Bulletin|website=www.loc.gov|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112051533/http://www.loc.gov/loc/lcib/9812/film.html|archive-date=January 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She next appeared in the drama [[The King of Marvin Gardens|''The King of Marvin Gardens'']] in 1972, with [[Jack Nicholson]], [[Bruce Dern]], and [[Scatman Crothers]]. A story about a daydreamer who convinces his brother to help fund one a get-rich-quick scheme, the film was well received by critics.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Last Picture Show (1971)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/last_picture_show|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105073617/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/last_picture_show|archive-date=January 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Linda Blair and Ellen Burstyn in The Exorcist.jpg|alt=Burstyn and Blair in The Exorcist (1973)|thumb|228x228px|Burstyn and Blair in ''The Exorcist'' (1973).]]\nIn 1972, Burstyn was keen on playing the lead role as Chris MacNeil in the supernatural horror, ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'' (1973). The film studio were initially reluctant to cast her, but when no other actors were put forward, Burstyn was secured the part. Her co-stars were [[Max von Sydow]], [[Lee J. Cobb]], [[Kitty Winn]], [[Jack MacGowran]], [[Jason Miller (playwright)|Jason Miller]] and [[Linda Blair]]. ''The Exorcist'' had a production budget of $12 million and its [[principal photography]] was held in various parts of New York City. Filming proved to be challenging for the entire cast, as it took \"six day weeks, twelve hour days for nine months\" to film and director William Friedkin would use a [[Theatrical property|prop gun]] to get genuine shocked reactions.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bramesco|first=Charles|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/24/william-friedkin-interview-exorcist-director-you-dont-know-a-damn-thing-and-neither-do-i|title=William Friedkin: 'You don\u2019t know a damn thing, and neither do I'|date=2018-04-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301141310/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/24/william-friedkin-interview-exorcist-director-you-dont-know-a-damn-thing-and-neither-do-i|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn also injured her [[coccyx]], which led to permanent injury to her spine.<ref>[http://blog.koldcast.tv/2011/koldcast-news/10-creepy-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-exorcist/ 10 Creepy Things You Didn't Know About The Exorcist - The Sixth Wall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121102305/http://blog.koldcast.tv/2011/koldcast-news/10-creepy-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-exorcist/ |date=January 21, 2013 }}. Blog.koldcast.tv (May 6, 2014). Retrieved 2014-06-05.</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] praised Burstyn for capturing her character's \"frustration\" during her daughter's possession by an evil spirit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-exorcist-1973|title=The Exorcist movie review & film summary (1973) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102153840/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-exorcist-1973|archive-date=November 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Against expectations, ''The Exorcist'' was a commercial success at the theaters. Adjusted for inflation, the film is the ninth [[List of highest-grossing films in the United States and Canada#Adjusted%20for%20ticket-price%20inflation|highest-grossing film of all time in the U.S. and Canada]] and the top-grossing R-rated film of all time. The film won two Academy Awards\u2014[[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] and [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]]\u2014and gained Burstyn a [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] nomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.strangemag.com/exorcistpage1.html|title=Part I - The Haunted Boy: the Inspiration for the Exorcist|website=www.strangemag.com|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003052203/http://www.strangemag.com/exorcistpage1.html|archive-date=October 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/16331/The-Exorcist/awards|title=The Exorcist|last=|first=|date=2012-10-22|website=The New York Times|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022111432/http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/16331/The-Exorcist/awards|archive-date=2012-10-22|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\nBurstyn followed up with a small role in the comedy-drama, ''[[Harry and Tonto]]'' in 1974. Her next major role was in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]'' (1975) where she played a widowed woman, raising a son and yearning to start a new life for herself as a singer. Drawn to the script, Burstyn selected then-newcomer Scorsese as director and recalled the collaboration as \"one of the best experiences I've ever had\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Benjamin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/26/ellen-burstyn-women-on-screen-were-prostitutes-or-victims-i-wanted-to-embody-a-hero|title=Ellen Burstyn: 'Women on screen were prostitutes or victims \u2013 I wanted to embody a hero'|date=2018-04-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311043952/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/26/ellen-burstyn-women-on-screen-were-prostitutes-or-victims-i-wanted-to-embody-a-hero|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"Burstyn never misses the eccentric beat that distinguishes it\u2014that makes Alice such a hugely appealing character who is both banal and very rare.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Canby|first=Vincent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/02/02/archives/flim-view-terrific-toughtakling-alice.html|title=Film View|date=1975-02-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301192736/https://www.nytimes.com/1975/02/02/archives/flim-view-terrific-toughtakling-alice.html|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The film earned her Academy Award for Best Actress.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Modderno|first=Craig|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/16/movies/shirley-maclaines-words-of-wisdom.html|title=Shirley MacLaine's Words of Wisdom|date=2005-10-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928121524/https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/16/movies/shirley-maclaines-words-of-wisdom.html|archive-date=September 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1975, she became a graduate of the first group of participants in the [[American Film Institute]] [[Directing Workshop for Women]]. In 1977, she was a member of the jury at the [[27th Berlin International Film Festival]] which was held in Berlin.<ref name=\"Berlinale 1977\">{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1977/04_jury_1977/04_Jury_1977.html|title=Berlinale 1977: Juries|work=berlinale.de|accessdate=July 19, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418172522/https://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1977/04_jury_1977/04_Jury_1977.html|archive-date=April 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe had supporting roles in ''[[Providence (1977 film)|Providence]] and [[A Dream of Passion]]'' in 1977 and 1978, respectively. Although these were independent dramas and not widely seen, the latter was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Film]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/film/dream-passion|title=Dream of Passion, A|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> Also in 1978, Burstyn starred in ''[[Same Time, Next Year (film)|Same Time, Next Year]]'' opposite [[Alan Alda]]'','' a romantic-comedy about two people, married to others, who meet for a romantic tryst once a year for two decades. The film is based on a [[Same Time, Next Year (play)|1975 play of the same title]] by Bernard Slade. Upon its release on November 22, the film garnered mixed reviews, with [[Janet Maslin]] of ''The New York Times'' stating, \"Slade's screenplay isn't often funny, and it's full of momentous events that can't be laughed away\", but praises Burstyn for giving the role \"warmth and grace\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/11/22/archives/film-same-timetrysting-annually.html|title=Film: 'Same Time':Trysting Annually|date=1978-11-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301192734/https://www.nytimes.com/1978/11/22/archives/film-same-timetrysting-annually.html|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Same Time, Next Year'' was nominated for Academy Awards in [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Song]], and Best Actress for Burstyn.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1979|title=The 51st Academy Awards {{!}} 1979|website=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> In the Golden Globes Awards, she won [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress in a Motion Picture]], and the film received two other nominations\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor]] for Alda and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/film/same-time-next-year|title=Same Time, Next Year|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\nBurstyn hosted NBC's ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', a late-night [[sketch comedy]] and [[variety show]], in December 1980.<ref name=\"preston\">{{cite news|last=Preston|first=Marilynn|title=Tempo: No panic, yet, from new 'Saturday Night' boss|date=December 9, 1980|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=B12}}</ref> That year, Burstyn starred in the drama ''[[Resurrection (1980 film)|Resurrection]]'', a story about a woman who possesses strange powers after a surviving a automobile crash. She was nominated again for Best Actress in the Academy Awards and Best Actress in the Golden Globes.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1981|title=The 53rd Academy Awards {{!}} 1981|website=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203143244/https://oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1981|archive-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/film/resurrection|title=Resurrection|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215165807/http://www.goldenglobes.com/film/resurrection|archive-date=February 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1981, she starred in the biographical television movie ''The People vs. Jean Harris'' (1981), based on the real life murder of [[Herman Tarnower]], a well-known [[cardiologist]] and [[author]] of the best-selling book ''[[Scarsdale medical diet|The Complete Scarsdale Medical Diet]]''. Burstyn was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Best Actress in a Miniseries or Television Film]] in the Golden Globes for her portrayal of the murderer, [[Jean Harris]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/people-vs-jean-harris|title=People Vs. Jean Harris, The|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> She was also nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Actress in a Mini-Series or Movie]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/people-vs-jean-harris|title=People vs. Jean Harris|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616145923/http://www.emmys.com/shows/people-vs-jean-harris|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1981, Burstyn recorded \"The Ballad of the Nazi Soldier's Wife\" for [[Ben Bagley]]'s album ''[[Kurt Weill]] Revisited, Vol. 2''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kritzerland.com/weill2.htm|title=Ben Bagley's KURT WEILL REVISITED, VOL. 2|website=www.kritzerland.com|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>  \n\n=== 1985\u20132005: Television films and continued success ===\nBurstyn followed up the mid-1980s with a number of acting roles in ''[[The Ambassador (1984 American film)|The Ambassador]]'' (1984), [[Surviving: A Family in Crisis|''Surviving'']] (1985), ''[[Twice in a Lifetime (film)|Twice in a Lifetime]]'' (1985), ''Into Thin Air'' (1985), ''[[Act of Vengeance]]'' (1986), ''Something in Common'' (1986) and [[Pack of Lies|play adaptation]], ''Pack of Lies'' (1987). For ''[[Twice in a Lifetime (film)|Twice in a Lifetime]],'' she portrayed Kate, the wife that [[Gene Hackman]]'s character left for when he fell in love with another woman. ''Pack of Lies'' was nominated for three Primetime Emmy Awards, including another for Burstyn as Outstanding Actress in a Mini-Series or Movie.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/pack-lies-hallmark-hall-fame|title=Pack of Lies Hallmark Hall of Fame|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019220712/https://www.emmys.com/shows/pack-lies-hallmark-hall-fame|archive-date=October 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Burstyn starred in a [[ABC Studios|ABC]] television [[situation comedy|sitcom]], ''[[The Ellen Burstyn Show]],'' with co-stars [[Megan Mullally]] as her daughter and [[Elaine Stritch]] as her mother. Created by [[David Frankel]], it ran only for one season. In 1987, she appeared in ''[[Dear America: Letters Home from Vietnam]]'' and ''Look Away'', both were television movies. In 1988, she participated as a member of the jury for the [[38th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale 1988\">{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1988/04_jury_1988/04_Jury_1988.html|title=Berlinale: 1988 Juries|work=berlinale.de|accessdate=March 4, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418172438/https://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1988/04_jury_1988/04_Jury_1988.html|archive-date=April 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A variety of acting performances followed suit, including in the dramas [[Hanna's War|''Hanna's War'']] (1987), ''[[When You Remember Me]]'' (1990), ''[[Dying Young]]'' (1991) and ''[[Grand Isle (film)|Grand Isle]]'' (1991). In 1990, Burstyn won the [[Sarah Siddons Award]] for her work in [[Theatre in Chicago|Chicago theatre]].<ref name=\"siddons\">{{cite web| title=The Sarah Siddons Society Awardees| url=http://www.sarahsiddonssociety.org/awardees/| publisher=Sarah Siddons Society| accessdate=December 4, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224055722/http://sarahsiddonssociety.org/awardees/| archive-date=December 24, 2016| url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition to television movies, Burstyn appeared in ''[[When a Man Loves a Woman (film)|When a Man Loves a Woman]]'' (1994) with co-stars [[Andy Garc\u00eda|Andy Garcia]] and [[Meg Ryan]].\n\nIn 1995, she portrayed Judith in the comedy-drama ''[[Roommates (1995 film)|Roommates]]'' (1995). The film received negative reviews and was a commercial failure, but it did receive a nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup]] in the Academy Awards.<ref>{{Citation|title=Roommates (1995)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/roommates|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130154319/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/roommates/|archive-date=November 30, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1996|title=The 68th Academy Awards {{!}} 1996|website=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002000121/https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1996|archive-date=October 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Also that year, Burstyn appeared in [[How to Make an American Quilt|''How to Make an American Quilt'']] (1995), based on the [[How to Make an American Quilt (novel)|1991 novel of the same name]] by [[Whitney Otto]], which tells the stories of several generations of women who are part of the same [[quilting]] circle. Despite a mixed critical response, the cast received a nomination for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{Citation|title=How to Make an American Quilt (1995)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/how_to_make_an_american_quilt|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920121856/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/how_to_make_an_american_quilt|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/2nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|title=The 2nd Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards {{!}} Screen Actors Guild Awards|website=www.sagawards.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325024748/https://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/2nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|archive-date=March 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1998, Burstyn appeared in ''[[Playing by Heart|Playing By Heart]]'', a story of eleven ordinary people in Los Angeles who are connected in different ways. Some critics such as Roger Ebert viewed the film positively despite the lackluster performance at the box office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/playing-by-heart-1999|title=Playing By Heart movie review (1999) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602021057/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/playing-by-heart-1999|archive-date=June 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3345516033/weekend/|title=Playing by Heart|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n[[File:OIFF 2015-07-17 184409 - Darren Aronofsky.jpg|alt=Director Darren Aronofsky has worked with Burstyn twice.|left|thumb|213x213px|Director Darren Aronofsky has worked with Burstyn twice.]]\nBurstyn next found supporting roles in ''[[The Spitfire Grill]]'' (1996), about a woman starting a new life after being released from prison, and ''[[Deceiver (film)|Deceiver]]'' (1997), a murder crime drama. Although not box office hits, each film garnered mixed to positive responses, according to [[Rotten Tomatoes]], a film review aggregator.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Spitfire Grill (1996)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/spitfire_grill|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129082500/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/spitfire_grill/|archive-date=November 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Deceiver (1998)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/deceiver|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228113121/https://rottentomatoes.com/m/deceiver|archive-date=December 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Next, she appeared in [[James Gray (director)|James Gray]]'s [[The Yards|''The Yards'']] (2000) alongside a principal cast of [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Joaquin Phoenix]], [[Charlize Theron]], [[Faye Dunaway]] and [[James Caan]]. The crime drama was unpopular and a commercial failure, earning less than $1 million worldwide from a budget of $24 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1148880385/weekend/|title=The Yards|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302180604/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1148880385/weekend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Staff|first=Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/nov/05/guardianinterviewsatbfisouthbank1|title=Ellen Burstyn - part two|date=2000-11-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430200847/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/nov/05/guardianinterviewsatbfisouthbank1|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, director [[Darren Aronofsky]] offered Burstyn the role of Sara Goldfarb in ''[[Requiem for a Dream]]'' (2000). She initially rejected the part, objecting to the depressive nature of the story. However, Burstyn changed her mind after seeing Aronofsky's previous work.<ref name=\":1\" /> The film is based on the [[Requiem for a Dream (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Hubert Selby Jr.|Hubert Selby Jr]], which tells the story of four New Yorkers whose lives are affected by drug [[Substance dependence|addictions]]. For the role, Burstyn had to wear [[Fatsuit|fat suits]], lose weight and speak to women in Brooklyn \"to get their speech patterns and outlook on life - and how narrow that is.\" She added, \"their life is about getting enough money to put food on the table to feed their children, and that's it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/01/16/ellen_bursytn_requiemforadream_160101_interview.shtml|title=BBC - Films - interview - Ellen Burstyn|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824003906/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/01/16/ellen_bursytn_requiemforadream_160101_interview.shtml|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0101/14/sm.12.html|title=CNN Transcript - Sunday Morning News: Ellen Burstyn Discusses 'Requiem for a Dream' - January 14, 2001|website=edition.cnn.com|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129232002/http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0101/14/sm.12.html|archive-date=January 29, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn and her fellow co-stars, [[Jennifer Connelly]], [[Jared Leto]], and [[Marlon Wayans]], found the filming schedule of forty days challenging and intense.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/uncategorized/dreams-fulfilled-a-darren-aronofsky-interview/|title=DREAMS FULFILLED: A DARREN ARONOFSKY INTERVIEW {{!}} Film Threat|date=2000-11-10|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824182549/https://filmthreat.com/uncategorized/dreams-fulfilled-a-darren-aronofsky-interview/|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Requiem for a Dream'' premiered at the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]] and was released to theaters on October 6, 2000. The film was well received and praised for its visual style and depiction of drug abuse. [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' writes, \"Burstyn gives an award-caliber performance that is as raw and riveting as the movie that contains it\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/requiem-for-a-dream-118844/|title=Requiem for a Dream|last=Travers|first=Peter|last2=Travers|first2=Peter|date=2000-12-11|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302144123/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/requiem-for-a-dream-118844/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn was nominated for Best Actress in the 2001 Academy Awards.<ref name=\"NYT2\">{{cite news|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=OSCAR FILMS/ACTORS: An Angry Man and an Underused Woman; Ellen Burstyn Enjoys Her Second Act|first=Rick|last=Lyman|date=March 4, 2001|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/04/movies/oscar-films-actors-angry-man-underused-woman-ellen-burstyn-enjoys-her-second-act.html|access-date=February 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314042144/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/04/movies/oscar-films-actors-angry-man-underused-woman-ellen-burstyn-enjoys-her-second-act.html|archive-date=March 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 to 2002, Burstyn starred in the [[CBS]] television series ''[[That's Life (2000 TV series)|That's Life]]''. The series, set in suburban [[New Jersey]], ran for two seasons. Burstyn appeared in several more films, including ''[[Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood (film)|Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood]]'' (2002), ''[[Brush with Fate]]'' (2003) and ''The Five People You Meet in Heaven'' (2004). Burstyn starred in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of Martin Tahse's ''Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells All'', based upon [[Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells All|the novel of the same title]] by [[Allan Gurganus]]. The show played 19 previews and officially opened November 17, 2003. Due to unfavorable reviews, all performances after the opening night were cancelled.<ref name=\"one\">{{cite news|last=Hernanzez|first=Ernio|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/82850-Oldest-Living-Confederate-Widow-Tells-No-More-Show-Closes-on-Broadway/I%3E-Tells-No-More;-Show-Closes-on-Broadway|title=Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells No More; Show Closes on Broadway|date=November 18, 2003|work=[[Playbill]]|accessdate=December 4, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413155524/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/82850-Oldest-Living-Confederate-Widow-Tells-No-More-Show-Closes-on-Broadway/I%3E-Tells-No-More%3B-Show-Closes-on-Broadway|archivedate=April 13, 2014|df=mdy}}</ref>\n\n=== 2006\u20132015 ===\n[[File:EllenBurstyn07TIFF.jpg|thumb|Burstyn at the [[2007 Toronto International Film Festival]].|alt=Burstyn at the 2007 Toronto International Film Festival.|220x220px]]She provided a supporting role as the mother of two sons in the 2006 romantic drama ''[[The Elephant King]]''. The film originally premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival#2006 Tribeca Film Festival|2006 Tribeca Film Festival]], and opened in U.S. theaters October 2008.<ref name=\"goldstein\">{{cite web| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/27/us-elephant-idUSTRE49Q2BK20081027| title=Little \"Elephant\" roars at box office| last=Goldstein| first=Gregg| date=October 27, 2008| agency=[[Reuters]]| accessdate=January 16, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413143726/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/27/us-elephant-idUSTRE49Q2BK20081027| archive-date=April 13, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2006, she starred as an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] bishop in the [[NBC]] comedy-drama series ''[[The Book of Daniel (TV series)|The Book of Daniel]]''. The series, which also starred [[Aidan Quinn]] as a drug-addicted Episcopal priest married to an alcoholic wife, was met with controversy from religious and spiritual leaders due to its unconventional portrayals of religious figures.<ref name=\"yonke\">{{cite news| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y3BPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YQQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6320,3337576| title='Book of Daniel' opens to controversy| last=Yonke| first=David| date=January 14, 2006| work=[[The Blade (Toledo)|The Blade]] (newspaper)| location=Toledo, Ohio| page=3| accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref> Conservative groups including [[American Family Association]] and [[Focus on the Family]] urged supporters to complain to NBC affiliates that carried the show. Subsequently, NBC removed the series from its line-up after four episodes, but did not publicly give a reason for doing so.<ref name=\"camacho\">{{cite news| url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/nbc-drops-book-of-daniel-from-lineup-5847/| title=NBC Drops 'Book of Daniel' from Lineup| last=Camacho| first=Justin| date=January 25, 2006| work=The Christian Post| accessdate=January 16, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413154552/http://www.christianpost.com/news/nbc-drops-book-of-daniel-from-lineup-5847/| archive-date=April 13, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>\n \nIn 2006, Burstyn appeared in the epic drama ''[[The Fountain (film)|The Fountain]]'', her second collaboration with Darren Aronofsky. Portraying Dr. Lillian Guzetti, the film is about a scientist (played by [[Hugh Jackman]]) struggling with mortality and is seeking a medical breakthrough to save his wife ([[Rachel Weisz]]) from cancer. Budgeted at $35 million, the screenplay is a blend of [[Fantasy film|fantasy]], [[Historical drama|history]], [[spirituality]], and [[Science fiction film|science fiction]]. ''The Fountain'' premiered on November 22, 2006 to mixed reviews from critics and under-performed at the box office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0414993/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|title=The Fountain|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=The Fountain (2006)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_fountain|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729221135/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_fountain/|archive-date=July 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ruthe Stein of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' writes, \"The movie is overloaded with imagery. At times, it's stunning to look at, but gradually becomes too much\", but praises Burstyn for her character's \"impressive depth\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/A-toke-worthy-search-for-fountain-of-youth-2545658.php|title=A toke-worthy search for fountain of youth|last=Stein|first=Ruthe|date=2006-11-22|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302202000/https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/A-toke-worthy-search-for-fountain-of-youth-2545658.php|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Since its release, the film has gained a [[Cult film|cult following]] causing media to revisit the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-fountain-explained/|title=\u2018The Fountain\u2019 Has Nothing to Do with Time|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=2016-11-22|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107234618/https://collider.com/the-fountain-explained/|archive-date=January 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2006, she was nominated for an Emmy Award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Mini-Series or Movie]] for the role of Former [[Herman Tarnower|Tarnower]] Steady in [[HBO]]'s ''[[Mrs. Harris]]'', another biopic about Jean Harris.<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2006/supporting-actress-movie-miniseries|title=Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie - 2006|publisher=emmys.com|accessdate=December 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206092827/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2006/supporting-actress-movie-miniseries|archive-date=December 6, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Soon after the nominations were announced, questions were raised regarding the worthiness of the nomination due to her minor role in the film, consisting of 14 seconds of screen time and 38 words of dialogue. The nominating committee were accused of approving a \"familiar\" name without actually seeing their performance.<ref name=\"bianco\">{{cite news|last=Bianco|first=Robert|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/televisionawards/emmys/2006-08-24-emmy-main_x.htm|title=Emmys need a fast fix|date=August 27, 2006|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=December 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628231004/http://www.usatoday.com/life/television/televisionawards/emmys/2006-08-24-emmy-main_x.htm|archive-date=June 28, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]], administrator of the Emmy Awards, insisted it was a legitimate nomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/popculture/emmy-14-seconds-worth-work-wbna14253083|title=An Emmy for 14 seconds worth of work?|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605100135/https://www.today.com/popculture/emmy-14-seconds-worth-work-wbna14253083|archive-date=June 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn reacted, \"I thought it was fabulous. My next ambition is to get nominated for seven seconds, and ultimately, I want to be nominated for a picture in which I don't even appear\", adding, \"This doesn't have anything to do with me ... work it out yourself.\"<ref name=\"emmynod\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2006-11-03-burstyn_x.htm|title=Ellen Burstyn Sounds Off on Her Emmy Nod|date=November 3, 2006|work=USA Today|accessdate=December 4, 2013|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710075804/http://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2006-11-03-burstyn_x.htm|archive-date=July 10, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Ultimately, [[Kelly Macdonald]], who starred in ''[[The Girl in the Cafe]]'', won the award.<ref name=\"scots\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/5292128.stm|title=Scots star wins Emmy for TV role|date=August 28, 2006|accessdate=April 13, 2013|publisher=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204101650/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/5292128.stm|archive-date=February 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2007, the Academy adjusted the eligibility criteria.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/16/AR2007031602142.html|title=Emmy Rules Change After Burstyn Nomination Flap|author=[[Lisa de Moraes]]|date=March 17, 2007|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 13, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026085000/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/16/AR2007031602142.html|archive-date=October 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe also appeared in the thriller ''[[The Wicker Man (2006 film)|The Wicker Man]]'' (2006) which was a commercial flop and negatively received by critics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0450345/?ref_=bo_se_r_2|title=The Wicker Man|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=The Wicker Man (2006)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_wicker_man_2006|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103015421/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_wicker_man_2006/|archive-date=January 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, Burstyn starred in ''[[The Stone Angel (film)|The Stone Angel]]'', based on the 1964 [[The Stone Angel|novel of the same name]] by [[Margaret Laurence]]. Like its predecessor, the film also received negative reviews, with [[Stephen Holden]] of ''The New York Times'' writing, \"a film of tightly assembled bits and pieces that don\u2019t fit comfortably together despite clever dashes of magical realism connecting past and present ... it leaves you frustrated by its failure to braid subplots and characters into a gripping narrative.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Holden|first=Stephen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/11/movies/11ston.html|title=A Tenacious Matriarch Who Won\u2019t Go Quietly|date=2008-07-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302221419/https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/11/movies/11ston.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Ellen Burstyn 2009.jpg|alt=Burstyn at the 2009 Creative Arts Emmy Awards.|thumb|231x231px|Burstyn at the 2009 [[Creative Arts Emmy Award|Creative Arts Emmy Awards]].|left]]\nA succession of films including ''[[Lovely, Still]]'' (2008), ''[[The Loss of a Teardrop Diamond]]'' (2008) and ''[[The Mighty Macs]]'' (2011), were released in the late 2000s which found success to niche audiences. She then appeared in ''[[Main Street (2010 film)|Main Street]]'' (2010) and ''[[Another Happy Day]]'' (2011), small-scale features with mixed reviews. In addition to film roles, between 2007 and 2011, she had an occasional recurring role on the HBO television drama series ''[[Big Love]]'', playing the mother of [[polygamist]] wife Barbara Henrickson. Burstyn returned to the stage in March 2008, in the [[Off Broadway|off-Broadway]] production of [[Stephen Adly Guirgis]]'s ''The Little Flower of East Orange'', directed by [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]] in a co-production by [[LAByrinth Theater Company]] and [[The Public Theater]].<ref name=\"hernandez\">{{cite news|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/116511-The-Little-Flower-of-East-Orange-Starring-Ellen-Burstyn-Opens-Off-Broadway-April-6 |title=The Little Flower of East Orange, Starring Ellen Burstyn, Opens Off-Broadway April 6 |last=Hernandez |first=Ernio |date=April 6, 2008 |work=Playbill |accessdate=January 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105142841/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/116511-The-Little-Flower-of-East-Orange-Starring-Ellen-Burstyn-Opens-Off-Broadway-April-6 |archivedate=November 5, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> In addition to her stage work, Burstyn portrayed former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Barbara Bush]] in [[Oliver Stone]]'s biographical film ''[[W. (film)|W.]]'' in 2008.<ref name=\"walker-mitchell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/good-bad-ugly/2009/01/22/1232471466530.html|title=Good, bad, ugly|last=Walker-Mitchell|first=Donna|date=January 23, 2009|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=December 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924200024/http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/good-bad-ugly/2009/01/22/1232471466530.html|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she won a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress \u2013 Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]] for her portrayal of the [[bipolar disorder|bipolar]] estranged mother of Detective [[Elliot Stabler]] on NBC's [[police procedural]] ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8253188.stm|title=Fey wins Emmy for TV Palin spoof|date=September 13, 2009|accessdate=December 4, 2013|publisher=[[BBC News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413145948/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8253188.stm|archive-date=April 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, she joined the cast of ''[[Political Animals (miniseries)|Political Animals]],'' a television series about the life of a divorced former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]], serving as [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]]. ''Political Animals'' received generally favorable reviews from critics according to [[Metacritic]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Political Animals|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/political-animals|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824231528/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/political-animals|archive-date=August 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the 2013 Golden Globe Awards, the series was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Miniseries or Television Film|Best Miniseries or Motion Picture Made for Television]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/political-animals|title=Political Animals|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219014959/http://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/political-animals|archive-date=December 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn won an Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Mini-Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2013/outstanding-supporting-actress-in-a-miniseries-or-a-movie|title=Outstanding Supporting Actress In A Miniseries Or A Movie Nominees / Winners 2013|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301180025/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2013/outstanding-supporting-actress-in-a-miniseries-or-a-movie|archive-date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe portrayed the grandmother of Lou (played by [[Mackenzie Foy]]) in ''[[Wish You Well (film)|Wish You Well]]'' (2013). A year later, Burstyn and Foy worked together again in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s epic science fiction [[Interstellar (film)|''Interstellar'']].<ref name=\"sneider\">{{cite web| url=http://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/twilights-mackenzie-foy-join-christopher-nolans-interstellar-103436| title=Ellen Burstyn, 'Twilight's Mackenzie Foy Join Christopher Nolan's 'Interstellar' (Exclusive)| last=Sneider| first=Jeff| date=July 15, 2015| work=[[Sharon Waxman|The Wrap]]| publisher=thewrap.com| accessdate=July 15, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107101738/http://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/twilights-mackenzie-foy-join-christopher-nolans-interstellar-103436/| archive-date=November 7, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> Set in a [[Dystopia|dystopian]] future where humanity is struggling to survive, the film follows a group of [[Astronaut|astronauts]] who travel through a [[wormhole]] in search of a new home for humanity. The film grossed over $677 million in the worldwide box office, making it the [[2014 in film|tenth-highest-grossing film of 2014]]. She made a guest appearance in five episodes of ''Louie'' in 2014, and starred in a thriller'', [[The Calling (2014 film)|The Calling]],'' the same year. Burstyn played Flemming, the daughter of [[Blake Lively]]'s immortal character, in the film ''[[The Age of Adaline]]'' (2015). Production started in March 2014, and the film was released in April 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Blake Lively, Ellen Burstyn Set To Star In 'The Age of Adaline'|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/blake-lively-ellen-burstyn-set-to-star-in-the-age-of-adaline/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=January 7, 2014|date=October 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222062403/http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/blake-lively-ellen-burstyn-set-to-star-in-the-age-of-adaline/|archive-date=December 22, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016\u2013present ===\nIn 2016, she guest starred in five episodes of ''[[House of Cards (American TV series)|House of Cards]]'', a critically acclaimed political thriller. Burstyn was credited on a succession of low-budget films, including ''[[Custody (2016 film)|Custody]]'' (2016), ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]'' (2017), ''[[All I Wish]]'' (2017) and ''[[Nostalgia (2018 film)|Nostalgia]]'' (2018). Burstyn also starred in ''[[The Tale]]'', a mystery drama which premiered on HBO on May 26, 2018. Director [[Jennifer Fox (documentary filmmaker)|Jennifer Fox]] was praised for her direction and bringing the \"complex, haunting work\" to life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/23/sundance-jennifer-foxs-deeply-disturbing-the-tale-explores-the-maze-like-nature-of-memory/|title=Sundance: Jennifer Fox\u2019s Deeply Disturbing \u201cThe Tale\u201d Explores the Maze-Like Nature of Memory {{!}} The Village Voice|website=www.villagevoice.com|access-date=2020-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303214242/https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/23/sundance-jennifer-foxs-deeply-disturbing-the-tale-explores-the-maze-like-nature-of-memory/|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn served as an executive producer for Peter Livolsi's film, ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]'' (2017)'','' about her friend [[R. Buckminster Fuller]], in which she also stars in.<ref>[http://scienceandfilm.org/projects/514/house-of-tomorrow The House of Tomorrow] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915001704/http://scienceandfilm.org/projects/514/house-of-tomorrow |date=September 15, 2016 }} , Museum of the Moving Image (2018)</ref> As of 2014, Burstyn is working on directing her first feature film, ''Bathing Flo''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/aug/26/ellen-burstyn-direct-film-bathing-flo|title=Ellen Burstyn to direct her first feature-length film at 80|author=Ben Child|work=the Guardian|access-date=December 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826041653/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/aug/26/ellen-burstyn-direct-film-bathing-flo|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2014/08/ellen-burstyn-directing-debut-bathing-flo-movie-824337/|title=Ellen Burstyn To Direct First Movie \u2014 'Bathing Flo' - Deadline|author=Mike Fleming Jr|work=Deadline|access-date=April 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501123043/http://deadline.com/2014/08/ellen-burstyn-directing-debut-bathing-flo-movie-824337/|archive-date=May 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Burstyn played Katherine in an acclaimed Australian production of [[Mois\u00e9s Kaufman]]'s play, [[33 Variations]] at Melbourne's Comedy Theatre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.limelightmagazine.com.au/reviews/33-variations-cameron-lukey-neil-gooding-productions/|title=\u2605\u2605\u2605\u2605\u00bd 33 Variations (Cameron Lukey & Neil Gooding Productions)|website=Limelight|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBurstyn married Bill Alexander in 1950 and divorced in 1957. The following year, she married Paul Roberts, with whom she [[adoption|adopted]] a son named Jefferson in 1961. The couple divorced that same year.<ref name=timeline>{{cite web| title=Timeline\u2014A Chronology of Key Events from Lessons in Becoming Myself| url=http://www.ellenburstyn.net/timeline.htm| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307073245/http://www.ellenburstyn.net/timeline.htm| archivedate=March 7, 2011| publisher=archive.org| accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref> In 1964, she married actor [[Neil Nephew]], who later changed his name to Neil Burstyn. She described Neil Burstyn as \"charming and funny and bright and talented and eccentric\", but [[schizophrenia]] made him violent and he eventually left her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oprah.com/spirit/ellen-burstyn-and-sheryl-crows-live-lessons/all|title=Becoming Yourself|work=Oprah.com|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en-us}}</ref> He attempted to reconcile but they divorced in 1972. In her autobiography, ''Lessons in Becoming Myself'', Burstyn revealed that he [[stalking|stalked]] her for six years after their divorce, and that he broke into her house and raped her. No charges were filed, as [[spousal rape]] was not yet a crime. He committed suicide in 1978.<ref>(December 1, 2006).[http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/article/burstyn%20feared%20death%20as%20abusive%20husband%20stalked%20her_1015128 Ellen Burstyn\u2014Burstyn Feared Death as Abusive Husband Stalked Her\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010185418/http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/article/burstyn%20feared%20death%20as%20abusive%20husband%20stalked%20her_1015128 |date=October 10, 2008 }}. ''[[contactmusic.com]]''. Retrieved December 20, 2009.</ref>\n\nBurstyn was raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], but now affiliates herself with all religious faiths. Her spiritual journey began with [[Sufism]]{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}. She explains: \"I am a spirit opening to the truth that lives in all of these religions... I always pray to Spirit, but sometimes, it's to the Goddess. Sometimes, it's to [[Jesus]]... Sometimes, I pray to [[Ganesha]] if I need an obstacle removed. [[Guan Yin]] is one of my favorite manifestations of the divine, the embodiment of compassion... So, I have Guan Yin with me all the time.\"<ref name=\"reiss\">{{cite web| title=Ellen Burstyn's True Face| url=http://www.beliefnet.com/Entertainment/Celebrities/Ellen-Burstyns-True-Face.aspx?p=1#| publisher=[[Beliefnet]]| year=2006| accessdate=December 4, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105035541/http://www.beliefnet.com/Entertainment/Celebrities/Ellen-Burstyns-True-Face.aspx?p=1| archive-date=January 5, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn has stated that in her late 30s she began to delve into the spiritual realm, coming under the tutelage of Sufi teacher Pir [[Vilayat Inayat Khan]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}; he gave her the spiritual name Hadiya,{{cn|date=April 2020}}<!--{{sfn|p=209}}--> which means \"she who is guided\" in [[Arabic]].\n\nDuring the 1970s, Burstyn was active in the movement to free convicted boxer [[Rubin Carter|Rubin \"Hurricane\" Carter]] from jail.<ref name=\"carter\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-02-20/news/mn-11377_1_carter-hurricane-seeking/16/AR2007031602142.html|title=N.J. Won't Seek a Retrial of Hurricane Carter|date=February 20, 1988|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=December 4, 2013|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120717005948/http://articles.latimes.com/1988-02-20/news/mn-11377_1_carter-hurricane-seeking/16/AR2007031602142.html|archive-date=July 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> She is a supporter of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/05/ellen-burstyn-interview-house-of-cards-netflix-1201751198/|title=Ellen Burstyn On \u2018House Of Cards\u2019 And The Presidential Race: \u201cI\u2019m Just Stunned\u201d|last=Utichi|first=Joe|last2=Utichi|first2=Joe|date=2016-05-19|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108125013/https://deadline.com/2016/05/ellen-burstyn-interview-house-of-cards-netflix-1201751198/|archive-date=November 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and appeared in the 2009 documentary ''[[PoliWood]]''. Burstyn served as president of the [[Actors' Equity Association]] from 1982 to 1985.<ref name=\"equity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.actorsequity.org/aboutequity/howigotmyequitycard/Ecard_burstyn.asp|title=How I Got My Equity Card|publisher=[[Actors' Equity Association]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021042600/http://www.actorsequity.org/AboutEquity/HowIGotMyEquityCard/Ecard_Burstyn.asp|archivedate=October 21, 2013|accessdate=December 4, 2013|df=mdy}}</ref> Burstyn is on the Board of Selectors of [[Jefferson Awards for Public Service]].<ref name=\"jefferson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jeffersonawards.org/board|title=Our Board of Selectors|publisher=Jefferson Awards for Public Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124055949/http://www.jeffersonawards.org/board|archivedate=November 24, 2010|accessdate=December 4, 2013|df=mdy}}</ref> In 1997, Burstyn was inducted into the [[Michigan Women's Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"MIwomens\">{{cite web|url=http://hall.michiganwomen.org/honoree.php?C=0&A=129~88~248~143|title=Ellen Burstyn: Michigan's Women's Hall of Fame|publisher=michiganwomen.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914070705/http://hall.michiganwomen.org/honoree.php?C=0&A=129~88~248~143|archivedate=September 14, 2015|accessdate=December 4, 2013|df=mdy}}</ref> Since 2000, she has been co-president of the [[Actors Studio]], alongside [[Al Pacino]] and [[Alec Baldwin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theactorsstudio.org/who-we-are/leadership/|title=Leadership|website=The Official Site of The Actors Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231183212/https://theactorsstudio.org/who-we-are/leadership/|archive-date=December 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013, she was inducted into the [[American Theatre Hall of Fame]] for her work on stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/whoopi-goldberg-to-host-the-30th-annual-musical-ce_67132.html|title=Whoopi Goldberg to Host the 30th Annual Musical Celebration of Broadway Honoring Neil Patrick Harris {{!}} TheaterMania|website=www.theatermania.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217162252/https://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/whoopi-goldberg-to-host-the-30th-annual-musical-ce_67132.html|archive-date=February 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1964\n| ''[[Goodbye Charlie]]''\n| Franzie Salzman\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Credited as Ellen McRae\n|-\n| ''[[For Those Who Think Young (film)|For Those Who Think Young]]''\n| Dr. Pauline Thayer\n|-\n| 1969\n| ''[[Pit Stop (1969 film)|Pit Stop]]'' (original title: ''The Winner'')\n| Ellen McLeod\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1970\n| ''[[Alex in Wonderland]]''\n| Beth Morrison\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Tropic of Cancer (film)|Tropic of Cancer]]''\n| Mona Miller\n|\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''{{sortname|The|Last Picture Show}}''\n| Lois Farrow\n| \n|-\n| 1972\n| ''{{sortname|The|King of Marvin Gardens}}''\n| Sally\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''{{sortname|The|Exorcist|dab=film}}''\n| Chris MacNeil\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1974\n| ''[[Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]''\n| Alice Hyatt\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Harry and Tonto]]''\n| Shirley Mallard\n|\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Providence (1977 film)|Providence]]''\n| Sonia Langham\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1978\n| ''{{sortname|A|Dream of Passion}}''\n| Brenda\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Same Time, Next Year (film)|Same Time, Next Year]]''\n| Doris\n| \n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Resurrection (1980 film)|Resurrection]]''\n| Edna Mae McCauley\n| \n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Silence of the North]