and Phytogeography of ''Eupatorium'' (Eupatorieae, Asteraceae): Insights from Sequence Data of the nrDNA ITS Regions and cpDNA RFLP | url = | journal = Journal of Plant Research | volume = 113 | issue = 1| pages = 79\u201389 | doi = 10.1007/PL00013913 }}\n* {{aut|Lamont, E.E.}} (1995): ''Taxonomy of ''Eupatorium'' Section ''Verticillata'' (Asteraceae)''. New York Botanical Garden Press. <small>{{ISBN|0-89327-391-0}}</small>\n* {{aut|Longe, Jacqueline L.}} (2005): ''The Gale Encyclopedia of Alternative Medicine'' (2nd ed., vol. 1). Gale Group, New York. <small>{{ISBN|0-7876-7424-9}}</small>\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 10811796 | volume=87 | issue=5 | title=Phylogeny and biogeography of Eupatorium (Asteraceae: Eupatorieae) based on nuclear ITS sequence data | date=May 2000 | journal=Am. J. Bot. | pages=716\u201326 | author=Schmidt GJ, Schilling EE | doi=10.2307/2656858 }} [http://www.amjbot.org/cgi/reprint/87/5/716.pdf PDF]\n* {{cite journal | author = Sharma Om P., Dawra Rajinder K., Kurade Nitin P., Sharma Pritam D. | year = 1999 | title = A review of the toxicosis and biological properties of the genus ''Eupatorium'' | url = | journal = Natural Toxins | volume = 6 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201314 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1522-7189(199802)6:1<1::AID-NT3>3.0.CO;2-E }}\n* {{cite journal | author = Whittemore Alan | year = 1987 | title = The Sectional Nomenclature of ''Eupatorium'' (Asteraceae) | url = | journal = [[Taxon (journal)|Taxon]] | volume = 36 | issue = 3| pages = 618\u2013620 | doi = 10.2307/1221856 }}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1123970}}\n\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Eupatorium| ]]\n[[Category:Asteraceae genera]]\n[[Category:Poisonous plants]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genus of plants}}\n{{For|the Crimean town|Eupatoria (disambiguation){{!}}Eupatoria}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n|image = Eupatorium cannabinum ziedai, 2006-07-22.JPG\n|image_caption = ''[[Eupatorium cannabinum]]''\n|display_parents = 3\n|taxon = Eupatorium\n|authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]] 1753 not Bubani 1899 ([[Rosaceae]])<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/NameSearch.aspx?name=Eupatorium&commonname= Tropicos search for Eupatorium]</ref>\n|synonyms_ref=<ref>[https://archive.is/20141123130650/http://dixon.iplantcollaborative.org/CompositaeWeb/default.aspx?Page=NameDetails&TabNum=0&NameId=adacbcf6-7341-4a54-a17c-c297cecc528d Flann, C (ed) 2009+ Global Compositae Checklist ]</ref>\n|synonyms=\n* ''Eupatorium'' sect. ''Pteropoda'' <small>DC.</small>\n* ''Eupatorium'' sect. ''Subimbricata'' <small>Hoffm.</small>\n* ''[[Viereckia]]'' <small>R.M.King & H.Rob.</small>\n* ''[[Chrone]]'' <small>Dulac</small>\n* ''[[Cunigunda]]'' <small>Bubani</small>\n* ''[[Pseudokyrsteniopsis]]'' <small>R.M.King & H.Rob.</small>\n* ''Eupatorium'' sect. ''Heterolepis'' <small>Baker</small>\n* ''[[Eriopappus]]'' <small>Hort. ex Loudon</small>\n* ''[[Caradesia]]'' <small>Raf.</small>\n* ''Eupatorium'' sect. ''Dalea'' <small>Loudon</small>\n* ''[[Eupatoriastrum]]'' <small>Greenm.</small>\n* ''[[Halea]]'' <small>L.</small>\n* ''[[Eupatoriadelphus]]'' <small>R.M.King & H.Rob.</small>\n|}}\n\n'''''Eupatorium''''' is a [[genus]] of [[flowering plant]]s in the [[Aster (genus)|aster]] family, [[Asteraceae]], containing from 36 to 60 [[species]] depending on the classification system. Most are [[Herbaceous plant|herbaceous]] [[perennial plant|perennial]]s growing to {{convert|0.5-3 |m|ft|abbr=on}} tall. A few are [[shrub]]s. The genus is native to [[temperate]] regions of the [[Northern Hemisphere]]. Most are commonly called '''bonesets''', '''thoroughworts''' or '''snakeroots''' in North America. The genus is named for [[Mithridates VI of Pontus|Mithridates Eupator]], king of [[Kingdom of Pontus|Pontus]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NJ6PyhVuecwC|title=The Names of Plants|first=David |last=Gledhill|edition=4|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-86645-3|year=2008|page=159}}</ref>\n\n==Systematics and taxonomy==\n''Eupatorium'' has at times been held to contain as many as 800 species,<ref>Whittemore (1987)</ref> but many of these have been moved (at least by some authors) to other genera, including ''[[Ageratina]]'', ''[[Chromolaena]]'',\n''[[Condylidium]]'', ''[[Conoclinium]]'', ''[[Critonia]]'', ''[[Cronquistianthus]]'', ''[[Eutrochium]]'', ''[[Fleischmannia]]'', ''[[Flyriella]]'', ''[[Hebeclinium]]'', ''[[Koanophyllon]]'', ''[[Mikania]]'', and ''[[Tamaulipa]]''.<ref>King, R. M. and H. Robinson. 1987. The genera of Eupatorieae (Asteraceae). Monographs in Systematic Botany, Missouri Botanical Garden 22: 1-581.</ref>\n\nThe classification of the tribe [[Eupatorieae]], including species placed in ''Eupatorium'' in the present or past, is an area of ongoing research, so further changes are likely. What seems fairly certain by now is that there is a [[Monophyly|monophyletic]] group containing ''Eupatorium'' (about 42 species of white flowered plants in North America, Europe and Asia, but not South America) and the Joe-pye weeds (''[[Eutrochium]]''), and possibly others.<ref>Ito ''et al.'' (2000), Schmidt & Schilling (2006)</ref>\n\n==Uses==\n''Eupatorium'' are grown as [[ornamental plant]]s, in particular in Asia.<ref name=\"yohei\">{{cite journal|title=Study on Eupatorium Plants Called \"Fujibakama\"|author1=Sasaki Yohei|author2=Matsumoto Atsushi|author3=Takido Michio|author4=Yoshimura Mamoru|author5=Nagumo Seiji|journal=Japanese Journal of Pharmacognosy|issn=1349-9114|volume=60|issue=1|pages=15\u201320|year=2006|url=http://sciencelinks.jp/j-east/article/200612/000020061206A0368406.php|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822025057/http://sciencelinks.jp/j-east/article/200612/000020061206A0368406.php|archivedate=2008-08-22}}</ref> A number of popular ornamental plants formerly included in ''Eupatorium'' have been moved to other genera, such as ''[[Bartlettina]]'' and ''[[Conoclinium]]''.\n\n[[Tobacco leaf curl virus]] is a [[pathogen]] occasionally affecting plants of this genus. The foliage is eaten by some [[Lepidoptera]] larvae, including those of ''[[Orthonama obstipata]]'' (The Gem).\n\n===Medical use===\nThe common names for the plants are all based on the previous usage of one species, ''Eupatorium perfoliatum'', as an herbal medicine.  Despite its name, boneset is not used to treat broken bones,<ref>[http://www.herbs2000.com/herbs/herbs_boneset.htm]</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2014}} instead the common name apparently derives from the herb's use to treat [[dengue fever]], which was also called breakbone fever because of the pain that it caused. The name thoroughwort also comes from ''Eupatorium perfoliatum'', and refers to the perfoliate leaves, in which the stem appears to pierce the leaf (i.e. go through, note that in older usage \"thorough\" was not distinguished from \"through\", compare for example the word thoroughfare).\n\nBoneset, although [[poison]]ous to humans and grazing [[livestock]], has been used in [[folk medicine]],<ref>Sharma ''et al.'' (1999)</ref> for instance to excrete excess [[uric acid]] which causes [[gout]].\nCaution is advised when using boneset, since it contains [[toxic]] compounds that can cause [[liver]] damage.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}} Side effects include muscular tremors, weakness, and [[constipation]]; overdoses may be deadly.\n\n==Selected species==\n[[File:Eupatorium cannabinum3.jpg|thumb|right|[[Hemp-agrimony]], ''Eupatorium cannabinum'']]\n[[File:Eupatorium perfoliatum 001.JPG|thumb|right|[[Common boneset]], ''Eupatorium perfoliatum'']]\n\n===North America===\n* ''[[Eupatorium album]]'' <small>L.</small>&ndash; white thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt>Schmidt & Schilling (2000)</ref><ref name=fna>{{cite web|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=112351|title=Eupatorium|work=Flora of North America}}</ref>\n* ''[[Eupatorium altissimum]]'' <small> L.</small> &ndash; tall thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n*''[[Eupatorium anomalum]]'' <small>Nash</small> \u2013 Florida thoroughwort<ref name=fna/> [[apomictic]] hybrid derivative of ''[[Eupatorium mohrii]]'' and ''[[Eupatorium rotundifolium]]<ref name=systematics>{{cite journal|journal=Systematic Botany|volume=41|issue=3|pages=x\u2013y|year=2016|title=Systematics of the Eupatorium mohrii Complex (Asteraceae).|author1=Edward E. Schilling|author2=Kunsiri Chaw Siripun|doi=10.1600/036364416X692361}}</ref>\n* ''[[Eupatorium capillifolium]]'' <small>(Lamarck) Small</small> &ndash; dog-fennel<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium compositifolium]]'' <small>Walter</small> &ndash; Yankeeweed<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium godfreyanum]]'' <small>Cronquist</small>, [[apomictic]] hybrid derivative of ''[[Eupatorium rotundifolium]]'' and ''[[Eupatorium sessilifolium]]<ref>{{cite journal|journal=American Journal of Botany|volume=93|issue=2|pages=319\u2013325 |year=2006|title=Molecular confirmation of the hybrid origin of Eupatorium gaurav Singh godfreyanum (Asteraceae)|author1=Kunsiri Chaw Siripun |author2=Edward E. Schilling|url=http://www.amjbot.org/cgi/content/full/93/2/319|doi=10.3732/ajb.93.2.319|pmid=21646192}}</ref>\n* ''[[Eupatorium hyssopifolium]]'' <small>L.</small> &ndash; hyssop-leaved thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium lancifolium]]'' <small>(Torrey & A.Gray) Small</small> &ndash; lance-leaved thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium leptophyllum]]'' <small>DC.</small> &ndash; false fennel<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium leucolepis]]'' <small>(DC.) Torrey & A.Gray</small> &ndash; justiceweed<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium linearifolium]]'' <small>Walter</small> &ndash; (''Eupatorium cuneifolium'')<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium maritimum]]'' <small>E.E.Schill.</small> &ndash; [[apomictic]] hybrid derivative of ''[[Eupatorium mohrii]]'' and ''[[Eupatorium serotinum]]<ref name=systematics/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium mikanioides]]'' <small>Chapman</small> &ndash; semaphore thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium mohrii]]'' <small>Greene</small> &ndash; Mohr's thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n*''[[Eupatorium novae-angliae]]''  <small>(Fernald) V.I.Sullivan ex A.Haines & Sorrie</small> <ref name=fna/> [[apomictic]] hybrid derivative of ''[[Eupatorium paludicola]]'' and ''[[Eupatorium perfoliatum]]<ref name=relationships>{{cite journal|doi=10.3119/0035-4902(2007)109[145:ROTNEB]2.0.CO;2|year=2007|volume=109|pages=145|title=Relationships Of The New England Boneset, Eupatorium Novae-Angliae (Asteraceae)|author=Schilling, Edward E.|journal=Rhodora|last2=Leblond|first2=Richard J.|last3=Sorrie|first3=Bruce A.|last4=Weakley|first4=Alan S.|issn=0035-4902|issue=938}}</ref>\n* ''[[Eupatorium paludicola]]'' <small>E.E.Schill. & LeBlond</small> &ndash; swamp thoroughwort, until 2007 classified as part of ''[[Eupatorium leucolepis]]''<ref name=relationships/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium perfoliatum]]'' <small>L.</small> &ndash; common boneset<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium petaloideum]]'' <small>Britton</small> &ndash; showy white thoroughwort, often considered to be part of ''[[Eupatorium album]]''<ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium pilosum]]'' <small>Walter</small> &ndash; rough boneset, often considered to be part of ''[[Eupatorium rotundifolium]]''<ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium resinosum]]'' <small> Torrey ex DC.</small> &ndash; pine barren boneset<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Effect of cross proximity on progeny fitness in a rare and a common species of Eupatorium (Asteraceae)|author=DL Byers|url=http://www.amjbot.org/cgi/content/abstract/85/5/644|journal=American Journal of Botany|volume=85|pages=644\u2013653|year=1998|doi= 10.2307/2446533|issue=5|jstor=2446533}}</ref>\n* ''[[Eupatorium rotundifolium]]'' <small>L.</small> &ndash; round-leaved thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium semiserratum]]'' <small> DC.</small> &ndash; smallflower thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium serotinum]]'' <small>L.</small> &ndash; late boneset, late thoroughwort<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium sessilifolium]]'' <small>L.</small> &ndash; upland boneset<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium sullivaniae]]'' <small>E.E.Schill.</small> &ndash; [[apomictic]] hybrid derivative of ''[[Eupatorium album]]'' and ''[[Eupatorium lancifolium]]<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Systematic Botany|volume=36|issue=4|pages=1088\u20131100|year= 2011|title=Systematics of the Eupatorium album complex (Asteraceae) from eastern North America.|author=Edward E. Schilling|doi=10.1600/036364411X605083}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n* ''[[Eupatorium cannabinum]]'' <small>L.</small> &ndash; hemp-agrimony<ref name=schmidt/><ref name=fna/>\n\n===Asia===\n[[File:Eupatorium makinoi2.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Eupatorium chinense|Eupatorium makinoi]]'']]\n* ''[[Eupatorium amabile]]'' <small>Kitam.</small><ref name=schmidt/><ref name=taiwan>{{cite web|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=100&taxon_id=112351|title=Eupatorium|work=Digital Flora of Taiwan}}</ref>\n* ''[[Eupatorium benguetense]]'' <small>C.Robinson</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium camiguinense]]'' <small>Merr.</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium chinense]]'' <small>L.</small><ref name=schmidt/><ref name=taiwan/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium formosanum]]'' <small>Hayata</small><ref name=schmidt/><ref name=taiwan/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium fortunei]]'' <small>Turcz.</small> &ndash; ''fujibakama'', ''pei lan''<ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium japonicum]]'' <small>Thunb.</small><ref name=dinghushan>{{cite web|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=620&taxon_id=112351|title=Eupatorium Linn.|work=Dinghushan Plant Checklist}}</ref> (often included in ''E. chinense''<ref name=\"china\">{{cite web|url=http://flora.huh.harvard.edu/china/mss/volume21/Asteraceae-AGH-Eupatorieae_coauthoring.htm|title=Asteraceae Tribe Eupatorieae (Draft)|work=Flora of China|accessdate=2009-12-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714220309/http://flora.huh.harvard.edu/china/mss/volume21/Asteraceae-AGH-Eupatorieae_coauthoring.htm|archivedate=2009-07-14}}</ref>)\n* ''[[Eupatorium lindleyanum]]'' <small>DC.</small><ref name=schmidt/><ref name=taiwan/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium luchuense]]'' <small>Nakai</small><ref name=schmidt/><ref name=taiwan/>\n* ''Eupatorium makinoi'' <small>T.Kawahara & T.Yahara</small> (see ''E. chinense''<ref name=china/>)\n* ''[[Eupatorium nodiflorum]]'' <small>DC.</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium quaternum]]'' <small>DC.</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium sambucifolium]]'' <small>Elmer</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium shimadai]]'' <small>Kitam.</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium squamosum]]'' <small>D.Don</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium tashiroi]]'' <small>Hayata</small><ref name=schmidt/><ref name=taiwan/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium toppingianum]]'' <small>Elmer</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium variabile]]'' <small>Makino</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n* ''[[Eupatorium yakushimaense]]'' <small>Masam. & Kitam</small><ref name=schmidt/>\n\n=== Moved to other genera ===\n* ''Eupatorium adamantium'' <small>[[George Gardner (botanist)|Gardner]]</small> (moved to ''[[Koanophyllon]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium amygdalinum'' (moved to ''[[Ayapana]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium ayapana'' &ndash; aya-pana, water hemp (moved to ''[[Ayapana triplinervis]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium bracteatum'' <small>Gardn.</small> (moved to ''[[Stomatanthes]], S. pernambucensis'') <!-- But see Flora uruguaya; enumeraci\u00f3n y descripci\u00f3n breve de las plantas conocidas hasta hoy y de algunas nuevas que nacen espontaneamente y viven en la Rep\u00fablica Uruguaya (1901) at https://archive.org/stream/florauruguayaenu03arec/florauruguayaenu03arec_djvu.txt which says \"Eupatorium bracteatum. Hook. y Arn. Comp. Bot. Mag. I. 239. no Gardner\" implying that E. bracteatum Gardn. and E. bracteatum Hooker & Arnott are two different species (moved to ''[[Chromolaena]] [[Chromolaena congesta|congesta]]]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asaweb.huh.harvard.edu:8080/databases/specimens?id=168989|title=ID 168989|work=Index of Botanical Specimens|publisher=Harvard University Herbaria}}</ref>) -->\n* ''Eupatorium coelestinum'' &ndash; mistflower (moved to ''[[Conoclinium]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium collinum'' (moved to ''[[Chromolaena]] collina'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nomen.at/Eupatorium%20collinum|work=nomen.at|title=Eupatorium collinum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.henriettesherbal.com/plants/eupatorium/collinum.html|title=Eupatorium collinum|work=Henriette's Herbal}}</ref>\n* ''Eupatorium itatiayense'' <small>[[Georg Hans Emmo Wolfgang Hieronymus|Hieron.]]</small> (moved to ''[[Symphyopappus]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium gayanum'' (moved to ''[[Aristeguietia gayana]]''<ref>[http://www.rain-tree.com/ayapana.htm Database entry Ayapana - Ayapana triplinervis - Ayapana - Eupatorium ayapana - Ayapana - Eupatorium triplinerve<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.chemfinder.co.uk/supplier_ms8888.html Fine Chem Trading (ChemFinder - UK) - Supplier MS8888<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>)\n* ''Eupatorium laevigatum'' <small>DC.</small> (moved to ''[[Chromolaena]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium ligustrinum'' (moved to ''[[Ageratina]] ligustrina''<ref>{{GRIN | ''Eupatorium ligustrinum'' | 16323 | accessdate = 14 December 2017}}</ref>)\n* ''Eupatorium maculatum'' (moved to ''[[Eutrochium maculatum]]'') Joe-Pye weed\n* ''Eupatorium maximiliani'' <small>[[Heinrich Adolph Schrader|Schrad.]] ex [[A. P. de Candolle|DC.]]</small> (moved to ''[[Chromolaena]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium megalophyllum'' (moved to ''[[Bartlettina sordida]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium officinale'' (moved to ''[[Mikania]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium pacificum'' (moved to ''[[Ageratina]]'')\n* ''Eupatorium purpureum'' 